{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"msg_1780165040873_1yoa8zyw8j8","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"claude-4.7-opus","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":" Looking at this patient's presentation: a 28-year-old male with acute upper respiratory tract infection, normal vital signs except for a slight fever at 37.6°C, and completely normal lab values including renal and hepatic function. He has no comorbidities, allergies, or current medications, which simplifies treatment considerations.\n\nThe clinical picture is straightforward—viral URTI with mild symptoms (cough with clear sputum, low-grade fever up to 37.8°C) that started three days ago after cold exposure. Physical exam shows only mild pharyngeal erythema with clear bilateral breath sounds, and the normal inflammatory markers (WBC, CRP, PCT) confirm this is viral and self-limiting. I'm recommending supportive care only: paracetamol as needed for fever above 38.5°C or pain, and ambroxol to help with cough and sputum clearance over five days. No antibiotics are warranted given the clinical and laboratory findings.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":50555,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"020de6b1-6997-463e-b146-893709f1f7fd","uuid":"7bbca196-32cd-40d4-b80f-1290c09a25c2"}
